metadata.name: ProcGen Entomology #483
metadata.description:
Realtime 3D in-browser procedural generation of insect-like models, with a look reminiscent of vintage entomology illustrations.

The project is about the fact that insects are cool first and foremost.
This is also about nostalgia.

Everything is procedural except for the font. The exposed features only describe the most visible parts.

I wrote mord words, about where it came from, and some technical details on the procedural aspect at:
https://ulucode.com/projects/entomology/

GPU Required!

Interface : 
Space : show/hide menu
Mouse Left : Rotate
Mouse Right : Pan
Mouse Middle/Wheel : Zoom

Captures only work in Live mode.

Ancient generative patterns.

Press 's' or double click/tap to save a PNG
To save 2x, 4x, or 8x versions, press the '2', '3', '4' keys respectively.

Made with thi.ng.

metadata.name: Reaching #62
metadata.description:
Reach for the stars.

However impossible it may seem, there's always a way. As long as you believe.
Everybody has a way to their stars, and the only way to reach it is to try as hard as you can and believe in yourself. I will forever live by this and believe in it.

A couple of the palettes used in this piece were adapted from the ever great Studio Yorktown, thank you for providing these incredible combinations of colors :)

--

Press spacebar or right click to save an image.

--

Reaching is a piece I dedicate to my recently passed grandmother. Rest in piece, we love you and miss you.

metadata.name: Supernal Memories #148
metadata.description:
With its layered bursts of color, light, and shadow, Supernal Memories carries an underlying message of optimism through its harmony of seeming dualities ‚Äì hard and soft, familiar and surprising, expression and introspection.

Each newly generated circle brings its own energy, creating layered groups of light that sometimes resemble phenomena like nebula, lightning sprites, and auras ‚Äì ethereal whispers of something remembered. 

Supernal Memories is an invitation to observe the forms & feel of each piece without labeling their qualities, to contemplate the infinite possibilities of the universe, and to explore the depths of your imagination.


--

Created by Diego Pintos @DondiegoTez
Creative collaboration with Tender @tender_art

To get a high resolution file, add "&print=14000" to the end of the live URL / hash, using any resolution number that fits your needs. Press 's' to save the file when it is done loading.

Press 'p' to continue the animation for another variation.

100% code, made with p5.js
See license.md

metadata.name: Triangle Subdivisions #537
metadata.description:
A study on geometric triangle subdivisions resulted in this artwork.
Only 638 bytes of JavaScript are needed to create a variety of different subdivisions (and no libraries are used). 

One tile will be generated for every byte of code.  

An article about this technique can be seen here:
https://josvromans.com/blog/2021/1/triangle-subdivisions/

metadata.name: Sketchbook Splash #158
metadata.description:
A splash of color on some scribbled shapes.

There are several keybindings to modify the image:
'1' - Toggles watercolors
'2' - Toggles overlaying constrast shapes 
'3' - Toggles sketch outlines
'4' - Toggles shape/splatter clipping (will fill the entire canvas with watercolor!)
'B' - Cycles borders; black, white, all colors in the palette being used, and no border

Play around to find something you like, and then press 'S' to download a copy of your image. 
You can also modify the URL parameters at the end of the URL to change the size of the image, such as &x=2560&y=1440. Keep in mind that this will result in a slightly different image, but colors/shapes/general layout will remain the same. The default size is 2048x2048.

@teaboswell, 2022

metadata.name: GuilCity #56
metadata.description:
GuilCity is the beginning of an exciting journey bringing Guillaume Cornet‚Äôs densely-packed cities into the generative realm with the help of Matthew‚Äôs (@frostbitten‚Äôs) magic touch.

Matthew‚Äîwith his background in coding and animation‚Äîenables a new opportunity to experience these cities like never before. Numerous elements from vehicles to characters and even architecture have been given life. Interact with the city (computer mouse only): poke and peek around (even behind) in this active search & find journey! 

Each generative city fills the composition with the type of whimsical, expressive elements and characters you‚Äôve come to know Guil for. What kinds of wacky features have you discovered yet?

‚Äî

The tech behind this project utilizes the highly compressed WEBP image format in order to provide so many full-color options. This format is great, but unfortunately Safari on desktop/laptop must be upgraded to at least version 14 and macOS to at least version 11 Big Sur to use it.

The animation system for this project was created from scratch with additional help from the PIXI.js library for individual mesh animations.

‚Äî

To find out more about your GuilCity, copy your unique operation hash and place it at the end of the following url:
‚Ä¢ https://my.guil.city?fxhash=
(for example: https://my.guil.city?fxhash=ooezL8cffNJGSc4TfNQp3u3WnDpkg8J3zFRczLuumceoYU5QYPs)

‚Äî


The entire process has been a learning experience for both of us, adapting and exploring the many possibilities to interact with each others‚Äô skills and ideas.

We really enjoyed building this project together and are excited as we invite you to take a dive into your very own urban playground!

Merci √† tous! Cheers!
  - Guillaume Cornet, Matthew Seremet

metadata.name: Metamorphosis #121
metadata.description:
This project uses cellular automata where the state of a cell in a new generation is determined based on its own and its neighbors' states in the previous generation. The guiding rules for these transitions, however, are not static; they undergo a random change every few generations, chosen from a possible 256 rules. By also slightly shifting the positions of cells and using an outline and texture that conveys a hand-drawn style, I have tried introducing an element of organic randomness.

Stepping away from the monochromatic color scheme used in my last three series, I have used a gradient effect to convey a transitioning hue across generations, combining a palette of two colors selected from an array of 14 different palettes. 

Note on the name: The alternating rules and fluctuating cell positions serve as the apparent justification for its name. However, a subtler inspiration lies in my deep admiration for Franz Kafka and his remarkable short story, "The Metamorphosis". Kafka‚Äôs narrative explores the constantly evolving state of human existence, where patterns appear momentarily only to dissipate quickly. Just when you think you've spotted a pattern, poof, it changes. Just like in life, right :)

Implemented in JS, this code utilizes the Perlin.js and Simple-noise.js libraries.

Press p to save a png of the image in full screen. Press s to save an svg file. 

Pixel Love!
